":"Cornwall, England","Devon, England":"Devon, England"},"nl":{"1198–20 January 1258":"1198–20 januari 1258","1203–1247":"1203–1247","1227–1284":"1227–1284","1198–1258":"1198–1258","1227":"1227","1226":"1226","8 August 1247":"8 augustus 1247","1215":"1215","1258":"1258","1247":"1247","1203":"1203","1224":"1224","1198":"1198","20 January 1258":"20 januari 1258","1284":"1284","Dunster, Somerset, England":"Dunster, Somerset, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Philleigh, Cornwall, England":"Philleigh, Cornwall, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England","Devon, England":"Devon, England"},"en":{"1198–20 January 1258":"1198–20 January 1258","1203–1247":"1203–1247","1227–1284":"1227–1284","1198–1258":"1198–1258","1227":"1227","1226":"1226","8 August 1247":"8 August 1247","1215":"1215","1258":"1258","1247":"1247","1203":"1203","1224":"1224","1198":"1198","20 January 1258":"20 January 1258","1284":"1284","Dunster, Somerset, England":"Dunster, Somerset, England, United Kingdom","Philleigh, Cornwall, England":"Philleigh, Cornwall, England, United Kingdom","Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England","Devon, England":"Devon, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Beauchamp","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Antoine, Jacques, Yves, Andre, Armand, Emile, Fernand, Marcel, Marthe, Remi, Alcide, Camille.","English (of Norman origin) and French: habitational name from any of several places in France, for example in Manche and Somme, that are named with Old French <i>beu</i>, <i>bel</i> ‘fair, lovely’ + <i>champ(s)</i> ‘field, plain’ (from Latin <i>bello campo</i> ‘beautiful field’). In English the surname is generally pronounced   Beecham  . Compare   Bushaw  .","English: in some cases, an Anglo-Norman French adaptation of Scottish   Campbell  , by translation into French of the folk etymology <i>de campo bello</i> ‘from the fair field’."],"variants":[{"name":"Beecham","meanings":["English (Lincolnshire): variant of   Beauchamp  , reflecting the normal English pronunciation."]},{"name":"Beachem","meanings":["English (Somerset and Gloucestershire): variant of   Beauchamp  ."]},{"name":"Beachum","meanings":["Altered form of English   Beauchamp  ."]},{"name":"Bagent","meanings":["English:","possibly a colloquial pronunciation of   Beauchamp   or   Beecham  . Old French <i>Beau-</i> often appears as <i>Be(e)-</i> in English surnames. The <i>-ch-</i> has been voiced and excrescent <i>-t</i> has been added.","perhaps an Anglicized form of a French or Flemish surname such as <b>Beaujean</b> and <b>Bejean</b>, from Old French <i>bel Jehan</i> ‘handsome John’ + excrescent <i>-t</i>. It could have been introduced to England in the 15th or 16th century by Flemish migrants."]},{"name":"Beacham","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Beauchamp  ."]},{"name":"Campbell","meanings":["Scottish: nickname from Gaelic <i>cam</i> ‘crooked, bent’ + <i>beul</i> ‘mouth’. As a result of folk etymology, the surname was often represented in Latin documents as <i>de bello campo</i> ‘of the fair field’, which led to the name sometimes being ‘translated’ into Anglo-Norman French as   Beauchamp  .","Irish (North Armagh): adopted for Gaelic <b>Mac Cathmhaoil</b> ‘son of Cathmhaol’ (literally ‘battle chief’): see   Caulfield   and   Cowell  .","English: variant of   Camel  , under the influence of the Scottish name (see 1 above)."]},{"name":"Bushaw","meanings":["Americanized form of French   Beauchamp   and   Bouchard  ."]},{"name":"Beacom","meanings":["English (Somerset) and Irish (Fermanagh): of Norman origin, a variant of   Beauchamp  ."]}]},{"name":"Michaell","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["feminine form of   Michael ."],"variants":[{"name":"Mikayla","meanings":["Modern respelling of   Michaela ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":17,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705188,"age":26,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Sir Michaell Beauchamp was born in 1198, in Cornwall, England. He married Merabell Durhall in 1226, in Philleigh, Cornwall, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died on 20 January 1258, in Devon, England, at the age of 60."},"et":{"1198–20 January 1258":"1198–20. jaanuar 1258","1203–1247":"1203–1247","1227–1284":"1227–1284","1198–1258":"1198–1258","1227":"1227","1226":"1226","8 August 1247":"8. august 1247","1215":"1215","1258":"1258","1247":"1247","1203":"1203","1224":"1224","1198":"1198","20 January 1258":"20. jaanuar 1258","1284":"1284","Dunster, Somerset, England":"Dunster, Somerset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Philleigh, Cornwall, England":"Philleigh, Cornwall, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England","Devon, England":"Devon, England"},"fi":{"1198–20 January 1258":"1198–20. tammikuuta 1258","1203–1247":"1203–1247","1227–1284":"1227–1284","1198–1258":"1198–1258","1227":"1227","1226":"1226","8 August 1247":"8. elokuuta 1247","1215":"1215","1258":"1258","1247":"1247","1203":"1203","1224":"1224","1198":"1198","20 January 1258":"20. tammikuuta 1258","1284":"1284","Dunster, Somerset, England":"Dunster, Somerset, Englanti, Yhdis